I have never been a fan of generating a priority order of epics as this ignores the fact that when the epics are broken down into stories the priorities are likely to change.

For example:

&gt;Epic A becomes Story X and Story Y
&gt;
&gt;Epic B becomes Story J and Story K

If the priority order of the stories is X, J, Y, K then which epic is the highest priority?

My recommendation would be to only do the story mapping on stories and avoid epics or themes as much as possible. 

I would attempt to do this in several phases:

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;First phase - first stab at the story mapping, defining themes/epics/stories.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Second phase - look at the story map and identify any epics or themes that look to be relatively high priority based on where they are in the map. Break these epics or themes down into stories.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Third phase - calculate value and effort for the stories in the story map that look to be relatively high priority.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fourth phase - Look at the map and taking into account value and effort decide if you need to change it around so that higher priority stories get done sooner.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Repeat any of the above phases if necessary until you are happy with the prioritisation and level of detail.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

